# GitHub workflow (team of 5)

Default branch: **`main`**. Remote: **`origin`**. Use **`gh`** for PRs/issues when the user asks.

## Before you start work

1. `git fetch origin`
2. `git pull origin main` (or pull your feature branch after rebasing on latest main)
3. Run `pnpm install` if `pnpm-lock.yaml` changed
4. Run `pnpm typecheck && pnpm test:transfer` — fix failures before new work

## Branching

- **Never force-push `main`** unless the user explicitly requests it.
- One person, one feature branch: `feat/<short-name>`, `fix/<short-name>`, or `shared/<change>`.
- **`shared/` contract changes**: branch `shared/<change>`, merge to `main` first, then everyone rebases/pulls before continuing backend/web work.
- Keep branches short-lived (1–2 days). Delete after merge.

## Committing

- **Only commit when the user asks.** If unclear, ask first.
- Stage focused changes; never commit `.env`, secrets, `keys/`, or local agent notes/config (ignored via local excludes).
- Message style: imperative, 1–2 sentences, focus on *why* (match existing log).
- After editing `shared/`, mention teammates must pull and rebuild: `pnpm --filter @mercato/shared build`.
- Before push: no AI-assistant names or attribution anywhere in tracked files, commit messages, or PR bodies.

## Pulling & staying up to date

```bash
git fetch origin
git pull --rebase origin main   # on your feature branch
```

- Prefer **rebase** over merge commits on feature branches (linear history).
- If already pushed and rebase rewrites history, use `git push --force-with-lease` **only on your feature branch**, never on `main`.

## Merge conflicts

1. `git fetch origin && git rebase origin/main` (or `git merge origin/main` if the team chose merge workflow).
2. Open each conflicted file; look for `<<<<<<<`, `=======`, `>>>>>>>`.
3. Resolve by keeping the correct combined logic — don't blindly pick "ours" or "theirs".
4. For `pnpm-lock.yaml` conflicts: accept one side, then run `pnpm install` and commit the regenerated lockfile.
5. For `shared/` conflicts: coordinate — contracts must stay consistent (types + schemas together).
6. `git add <resolved-files>` then `git rebase --continue` (or complete the merge commit).
7. Run `pnpm typecheck && pnpm test:transfer` before pushing.

## Pull requests (preferred for team review)

1. Push branch: `git push -u origin HEAD`
2. Create PR to `main` with `gh pr create`
3. PR body: Summary (what/why) + Test plan checklist
4. Wait for review or pair-approve before merge
5. Merge via GitHub (squash or merge commit — team default: **squash** for feature branches)
6. Delete remote branch after merge; locally: `git checkout main && git pull origin main`

## Direct push to main

Only when the user explicitly asks (e.g. solo hotfix). Still run pre-push checks:

```bash
pnpm typecheck && pnpm test:transfer
git push origin main
```

## Agent git safety (never break these)

- Never `git config` changes, `--no-verify`, or `push --force` to `main`
- Never skip hooks unless the user explicitly requests it
- Never amend a pushed commit unless the user explicitly requests it
- Never push `.env` or credentials

## Handoff when contracts change

When `shared/` lands on `main`, post in team chat (or PR comment):

> `shared/` updated on main — pull, `pnpm install`, `pnpm --filter @mercato/shared build`, then continue your branch.
